00:41:28,280 --> 00:41:31,280
let's talk about entropy in general.

672
00:41:31,280 --> 00:41:36,280
What is entropy, and how do you define it?

673
00:41:36,280 --> 00:41:39,280
We can define it either with precision or we can define it qualitatively.

674
00:41:39,280 --> 00:41:43,280
I prefer to define it qualitatively.

675
00:41:43,280 --> 00:41:48,280
To understand what entropy is, you need to understand what information is.

676
00:41:48,280 --> 00:41:51,280
And let me be very, very simplistic

677
00:41:51,280 --> 00:41:54,280
about what information is.

678
00:41:54,280 --> 00:41:56,280
Information you can...

679
00:41:56,280 --> 00:42:00,280
The information about a system.

680
00:42:00,280 --> 00:42:02,280
The information about a system.

681
00:42:02,280 --> 00:42:07,280
Let's not ask about what it is, but how do you quantify it?

682
00:42:07,280 --> 00:42:12,280
How much information is there in a system?

683
00:42:12,280 --> 00:42:19,280
Or better yet, how much information separates one system from another?

684
00:42:19,280 --> 00:42:20,280
What's the...

685
00:42:20,280 --> 00:42:22,280
What's the way that you...

686
00:42:22,280 --> 00:42:26,280
What's the way you explain to somebody the difference between systems?

687
00:42:26,280 --> 00:42:30,280
Well, you ask a bunch of questions about the system.

688
00:42:30,280 --> 00:42:33,280
I'm not even going to try to ask the question...

689
00:42:33,280 --> 00:42:35,280
Well, yeah, we could...

690
00:42:35,280 --> 00:42:36,280
We could...

691
00:42:36,280 --> 00:42:37,280
Here's a system.

692
00:42:37,280 --> 00:42:38,280
Here's a system.

693
00:42:38,280 --> 00:42:40,280
It's a big box.

694
00:42:40,280 --> 00:42:43,280
The box is broken up into little boxes.

695
00:42:43,280 --> 00:42:48,280
Those little boxes are about as big as an atom.

696
00:42:48,280 --> 00:42:50,280
And you can know everything about what's in there.

697
00:42:50,280 --> 00:42:54,280
What's in this box, if I tell you yes or no, whether there's an atom...

698
00:42:54,280 --> 00:42:58,280
I would have to tell you what kind of atom, but let's simplify it.

699
00:42:58,280 --> 00:43:01,280
There would have to be just one kind of atom in the world.

700
00:43:01,280 --> 00:43:04,280
And either a box is empty or a box is full.

701
00:43:04,280 --> 00:43:10,280
If I go through the boxes and tell you whether there's an atom there or not,

702
00:43:10,280 --> 00:43:13,280
I have told you just about everything about that box.

703
00:43:13,280 --> 00:43:16,280
There's an atom here, there's an atom here, there's an atom here, there's an atom here,

704
00:43:16,280 --> 00:43:18,280
there's an atom here, here, here, here.

705
00:43:18,280 --> 00:43:19,280
No other atoms.

706
00:43:19,280 --> 00:43:23,280
Well, then there's a block or a lump of stuff in the middle.

707
00:43:23,280 --> 00:43:24,280
Okay?

708
00:43:24,280 --> 00:43:25,280
Maybe that one's missing.

709
00:43:25,280 --> 00:43:28,280
Now it's a lump of stuff with a funny shape.

710
00:43:28,280 --> 00:43:31,280
So you can go through this thing with a bunch of yes-no questions.

711
00:43:31,280 --> 00:43:36,280
Is there or isn't there an atom in this box, that box, and so forth?

712
00:43:36,280 --> 00:43:40,280
Another way of describing information is to say,

713
00:43:40,280 --> 00:43:47,280
if I want to describe the system, what I need to do is give a code to describe it.

714
00:43:47,280 --> 00:43:49,280
And the code might simply be,

715
00:43:49,280 --> 00:43:52,280
a series of zeros and ones,

716
00:43:52,280 --> 00:43:53,280
where you go through this thing,

717
00:43:53,280 --> 00:43:56,280
00010110.

718
00:43:56,280 --> 00:44:00,280
In other words, it could be a long binary digit.

719
00:44:00,280 --> 00:44:02,280
How long?

720
00:44:02,280 --> 00:44:06,280
Well, it depends on how many bits of information you're trying to describe.

721
00:44:06,280 --> 00:44:11,280
How many yes-no questions it takes to describe a system completely.

722
00:44:11,280 --> 00:44:13,280
The number of yes-no questions,

723
00:44:13,280 --> 00:44:18,280
or the number of binary digits that you would have to prescribe,

724
00:44:18,280 --> 00:44:22,280
to describe a system, or to distinguish it from other systems,

725
00:44:22,280 --> 00:44:30,280
is called the information in the system.

726
00:44:30,280 --> 00:44:33,280
Information theorists use it all the time.

727
00:44:33,280 --> 00:44:37,280
And as I say, they characterize it in terms of bits.

728
00:44:37,280 --> 00:44:40,280
A bit is a yes-no question.

729
00:44:40,280 --> 00:44:41,280
Okay?

730
00:44:41,280 --> 00:44:45,280
And, okay, so,

731
00:44:45,280 --> 00:44:47,280
the quantity of information is characterized by the number of bits.

732
00:44:47,280 --> 00:44:50,280
In this system here,

733
00:44:50,280 --> 00:44:53,280
the number of bits would just be the number of boxes.

734
00:44:53,280 --> 00:44:58,280
The number of boxes where you might or might not have an atom.

735
00:44:58,280 --> 00:45:00,280
That's pretty clear.

736
00:45:00,280 --> 00:45:02,280
I mean, we could describe everything in this room

737
00:45:02,280 --> 00:45:06,280
by breaking it up into sufficiently small boxes.

738
00:45:06,280 --> 00:45:11,280
If we didn't want to deal with the fact that there were different kinds of elements,

739
00:45:11,280 --> 00:45:15,280
we could break it up into even smaller boxes

740
00:45:15,280 --> 00:45:17,280
and simply ask whether there were,

741
00:45:17,280 --> 00:45:21,280
well, I suppose we would have to distinguish electrons from quarks.

742
00:45:21,280 --> 00:45:26,280
But we could always break it down into yes-no questions.

743
00:45:26,280 --> 00:45:29,280
Is there a quark in this box?

744
00:45:29,280 --> 00:45:31,280
Isn't there a quark in this box?

745
00:45:31,280 --> 00:45:32,280
Is there an electron in this box?

746
00:45:32,280 --> 00:45:34,280
Isn't there an electron in this box?

747
00:45:34,280 --> 00:45:38,280
And eventually, we would learn everything there is to know about this room

748
00:45:38,280 --> 00:45:40,280
by asking that series of questions.

749
00:45:40,280 --> 00:45:43,280
The minimum number that it would take to describe the room

